To use the `removeAt()` method on a custom class list, you need to make sure that the list is mutable, meaning you can add or remove elements from it. Here's an example of how you can use the `removeAt()` method:

```
class CustomClass(val id: Int, val name: String)

val customList = mutableListOf<CustomClass>()

// Add some elements to the list
customList.add(CustomClass(1, "Element 1"))
customList.add(CustomClass(2, "Element 2"))
customList.add(CustomClass(3, "Element 3"))

// Remove an element at index 1
customList.removeAt(1) // this will remove the second element

// Print the remaining elements
for (element in customList) {
    println("ID: ${element.id}, Name: ${element.name}")
}
```

