We add three elements to the list using the `add()` method. We then remove the second element using the `removeAt()` method, passing its index (1) as an argument.

Finally, we loop through the remaining elements in `customList` and print their properties.

Note that if your custom class does not have an explicitly defined `equals()` and `hashCode()` method, then the `removeAt()` method will not work as expected. In this case, you may need to override these methods to ensure that your custom object is being compared properly.

